If you get a chance to live in an old house, which is in this case almost 400 years old. You will experience living in a summer and winter house. 

When the days get crispy, I prepare the house for the colder months. The woolly curtains are pulled up again, the thick blankets are placed in all the snuggle places, wood is stocked, candles come out and stews simmer in the oven for a comforting meal.

The whole atmosphere change of the house, which also brings excitement.

Welcome to the winter house.

‘Nos Galan Gaeaf’
It is celebrated the day before Winter, the ‘Ysbrydnos’ (Spirit Night) which represents both death and rebirth. 

Nos Calan Gaeaf was also the night to be aware of the Hwch Ddu Gwta or the black, tail-less sow – a huge black beast with red eyes that could crush the bones of any person who crossed its path and was said to seize souls and carry them off to the underworld.
Ghosts, witches and goblins were believed to appear at midnight on this night, especially on the entrances to footpaths, crossroads, stiles and churchyards. One of the most frequent ghosts which appear in Welsh folklore is the ‘y ladi wen’ (Lady in White)

In Pagan times Jack O’ lanterns - originally made from turnips – were used as a lantern to guide the dead back to earth. In later years, ugly and scary faces would be carved into swedes or turnips and placed in the windows to ward off evil spirits. Over time, they then became a common way to try and frighten people for fun where a carved turnip would be placed on the side of the road or path with a lit candle inside. Nowadays they have become a common decoration, with the easier to carve pumpkin replacing the turnip!

Coelcerth. A bonfire was built near the house, to frighten away any evil spirits. There would be dancing and singing. At the end of the evening, before leaving the fire to burn out, people would throw a white stone with their name written on it into the embers. The following morning, they would return to the remains of the bonfire to look for their stones among the ashes. Those who found them were granted good luck for the coming year. If, however, someone’s stone was missing, the person who threw it in would ‘die before he saw another All Saint’s Eve.’ Imagine the sleepless night you would have hoped your stone would be there!

Dear dirt, I am sorry I slighted you,
I thought that you were only the background
for the leading characters—the plants
and animals and human animals.
It’s as if I had loved only the stars
and not the sky which gave them space
in which to shine.  Subtle, various,
sensitive, you are the skin of our terrain,
you’re our democracy.  When I understood
I had never honored you as a living
equal, I was ashamed of myself,
as if I had not recognized
a character who looked so different from me,
but now I can see us all, made of the
same basic materials—
cousins of that first exploding from nothing—
in our intricate equation together.  O dirt,
help us find ways to serve your life,
you who have brought us forth, and fed us,
and who at the end will take us in
and rotate with us, and wobble, and orbit. 

by Sharon Olds

I’ll show you my happy place! ❤️ 

After 14 months of blood, sweat and tears, Studio 21 is now (almost😅) finished. This barn has been transformed back to life, which has simply rotted away for many years. This is truly one of my biggest dreams in life to come true. 

I made a lot by myself like the design, soft furniture and shelves. Still want to do a lot of things (for example the floor is not finished) but it comes with time. For now, I'm happy I have space where I can spread out. 

I worked with @littlegreenepaintcompany who kindly provided me with their incredible paints. Thank you so much! A big thank you goes also to Paul & Rob who help me with carpentry! 

I’m beyond happy to share it with you. I will continue to convert this space and am excited about future projects.

Fran xx

My cute little sewing corner 🧵🪡… 

There is a variety of furniture in this space. Most of it has been stored for years and has now been given a second life. The old piano chair has been updated with a new cushion that matches the curtain upstairs. The table is a small, old kitchen table that I decided to keep as my sewing table. As for my storage shelf, I made it myself using old pallet wood and a wine box.
